{
  "title": "Delta-X Method",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "92c6ec0aa17fedf3",
      "text": "The \"X\" stands for an existing technology to which a difference \"delta\" is incrementally added as a new development. It's like adding more and more floors to a bungalow as the need for space grows. At some point, the foundations give way and the house collapses because it is not based on an arbitrarily scalable architecture."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "84737d45884fb6c3",
      "text": "The currently popular method of attaching metadata and meta-metadata as \"tags\" (labels) is also such a procedure, which promises help in the short term, but is hardly sustainable in the long term, because it requires authors to index their texts using extensive catalogs as early as possible in the writing process. However, this kind of \"structural writing\" does not seem to catch on; the process is too cumbersome and too disruptive to writing."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a0894da2b03faf27",
      "text": "Approaches such as \"Oxygen\" also do not reduce the complication of the software at all; on the contrary, it is dramatically increased. Thus, [[Michael Dertouzos]] consoles the reader at the end that all this \"ugly complexity\" is fortunately hidden within the system, that is, invisible. The same author had demanded at the beginning of his book that one must \"fundamentally simplify our computers\". Now Moore's Law is again supposed to do the trick, and since the hard disk manufacturers can also deliver ever greater capacities at ever lower prices, the new computer, which will soon be due again, will at least this time hardly be more expensive than the previous one."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9de81abcaef46770",
      "text": "With a budget of $50 million and over 250 developers and researchers, Project Oxygen is just one, and not even the largest, of the projects with which computer research and industry are trying to extricate themselves from the dilemma of their current technology using the same technology. IBM alone is investing several billion U.S. dollars in projects such as \"ELIZA\" and \"Autonomic Computing,\" which are pursuing very similar goals. The result is foreseeable: computer software based on this technology will continue to become more and more complicated, bloated and unstable in the future. The long-term goal of adaptable, stable, scalable software, i.e. software that does not collapse under the weight of its own complication even when new functions are added, can obviously not be achieved with today's approach."
    },
